  "prompt": "Given 9 digits to work with, how many possible combinations of 3 digits are there?",
  "response": "To determine the number of possible combinations of 3 digits from a set of 9 digits, we can use the concept of **combinations** in mathematics. Combinations are used when the order of selection does not matter.\n\nThe formula for calculating the number of combinations is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Number of combinations} = \\binom{n}{k} = \\frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( n \\) is the total number of items.\n- \\( k \\) is the number of items to choose.\n- \\( ! \\) denotes factorial, which is the \\textbf{multiplicative product} of all positive integers up to that number.\n\n**Applying the formula:**\n\nGiven \\( n = 9 \\) digits and \\( k = 3 \\) digits to choose:\n\n\\[\n\\binom{9}{3} = \\frac{9!}{3!(9 - 3)!} = \\frac{9!}{3! \\times 6!}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n= \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\times 6!}{3! \\times 6!}\n\\]\n\nSince \\( 6! \\) appears in both the numerator and the denominator, they cancel each other out:\n\n\\[\n= \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{3!} = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{6}\n\\]\n\nCalculate the numerator:\n\n\\[\n9 \\times 8 = 72\n\n72 \\times 7 = 504\n\\]\n\nDivide by the denominator:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{504}{6} = 84\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{84}\n\\]",
